==Old English==
===Etymology===
From the Germanic: cognate with Old Frisian [[luve]], Old High German [[luba]], Gothic ''(𐌱𐍂𐍉𐌸𐍂𐌿) 𐌻𐌿𐌱𐍉'' ‘(brotherly) love’.
From Indo-Iranian. Old English lufu, luvu, or lubu, which derived from luba of Old High German. The luba of Old High German derived from leubh, lubet, and libet of Sanskrit and Old Aryan, meaning “pleasing.”

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'lʊvʊ/

